Definning the model¶

In [36]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

import pathlib
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from collections import Counter
from PIL import Image
import pandas as pd

# Path to dataset
data_folder = pathlib.Path('../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small')

# Retrieve all image paths and corresponding labels
image_paths = list(data_folder.glob('**/*.jpg'))
labels = [path.parent.name for path in image_paths[:2000]]  

# Collect statistics
stats = Counter(labels)

# Convert statistics to a DataFrame for easier handling
stats_df = pd.DataFrame(stats.items() , columns=["Label", "Count" ])
stats_df["Percentage"] = (stats_df["Count"] / len(labels)) * 100

# Plot statistics
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.bar(stats_df["Label"], stats_df["Count"])
plt.title("Distribution of Images by Label (Up to 2000 Images)")
plt.xlabel("Label")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.show()

# Optionally, print statistics
print(stats_df)

1   dog   1000        50.0

import os
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models
from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
import warnings

# Suppress warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

# Paths
train_dir = '../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/train'
validation_dir = '../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/validation'
test_dir = '../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/test'

# Image dimensions and batch size
IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH = 224, 224
BATCH_SIZE = 32

# Data augmentation and normalization
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1.0/255,
    rotation_range=20,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    fill_mode='nearest'
)

validation_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1.0/255)
test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1.0/255)

# Data generators
train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_dir,
    target_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary'
)

validation_generator = validation_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    validation_dir,
    target_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary'
)

test_generator = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test_dir,
    target_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary'
)

# Transfer Learning: VGG16 Model 1
def create_vgg16_model():
    base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH, 3))
    base_model.trainable = False  # Freeze the base model

    model = models.Sequential([
        base_model,
        layers.Flatten(),
        layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'),
        layers.Dropout(0.5),
        layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    return model

# Transfer Learning: VGG16 Model 2 (with fine-tuning)
def create_vgg16_finetuned_model():
    base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH, 3))
    base_model.trainable = True  # Unfreeze the base model

    # Fine-tune specific layers
    for layer in base_model.layers[:-4]:
        layer.trainable = False

    model = models.Sequential([
        base_model,
        layers.Flatten(),
        layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
        layers.Dropout(0.5),
        layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    return model

# Compile models
model_1 = create_vgg16_model()
model_1.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Callbacks for saving the best model
checkpoint_1 = ModelCheckpoint('best_model_1.keras', save_best_only=True, monitor='val_loss', mode='min')
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True)

# Train Model 1
print("Training Model 1")
history_1 = model_1.fit(
    train_generator,
    epochs=20,
    validation_data=validation_generator,
    callbacks=[checkpoint_1, early_stopping]
)

# Evaluate on test data
print("Evaluating Model 1 on test data")
test_loss_1, test_acc_1 = model_1.evaluate(test_generator)
print(f"Model 1 Test Loss: {test_loss_1}, Test Accuracy: {test_acc_1}")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_training_history(history, model_name="Model"):
    acc = history.history['accuracy']
    val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    epochs_range = range(len(acc))

    # Plot Accuracy
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, acc, label='Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_acc, label='Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title(f'{model_name} - Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend(loc='lower right')

    # Plot Loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, loss, label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label='Validation Loss')
    plt.title(f'{model_name} - Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models, optimizers
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, EarlyStopping
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Paths
train_dir = '../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/train'
validation_dir = '../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/validation'
test_dir = '../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/test'

# Image dimensions and batch size
IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH = 224, 224
BATCH_SIZE = 32

# Data augmentation and normalization
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1.0/255,
    rotation_range=20,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    fill_mode='nearest'
)
validation_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1.0/255)
test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1.0/255)

# Data generators
train_generator = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    train_dir,
    target_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary'
)
validation_generator = validation_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    validation_dir,
    target_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary'
)
test_generator = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test_dir,
    target_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary'
)

# Fine-Tune VGG16 Model
base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH, 3))
base_model.trainable = True

# Fine-tune the last few layers
for layer in base_model.layers[:-4]:
    layer.trainable = False

model = models.Sequential([
    base_model,
    layers.Flatten(),
    layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dropout(0.5),
    layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4),
              loss='binary_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Callbacks
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint('best_vgg16_finetuned_model.keras', save_best_only=True, monitor='val_loss', mode='min')
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True)

# Train the model
history = model.fit(
    train_generator,
    epochs=20,
    validation_data=validation_generator,
    callbacks=[checkpoint, early_stopping]
)

# Plot Training and Validation Metrics
def plot_training_history(history, model_name="Fine-Tuned VGG16"):
    acc = history.history['accuracy']
    val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    epochs_range = range(len(acc))

    # Plot Accuracy
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, acc, label='Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_acc, label='Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title(f'{model_name} - Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend(loc='lower right')

    # Plot Loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, loss, label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label='Validation Loss')
    plt.title(f'{model_name} - Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

plot_training_history(history, model_name="Fine-Tuned VGG16")

# Evaluate the best model on the test data
print("Evaluating Fine-Tuned Model on Test Data")
test_loss, test_accuracy = model.evaluate(test_generator)
print(f"Test Loss: {test_loss}, Test Accuracy: {test_accuracy}")

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report, precision_recall_curve, auc
from tensorflow.keras.models import load_model

# Paths
test_dir = '../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small/test'

# Reload test data generator
test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1.0/255)
test_generator = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    test_dir,
    target_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH),
    batch_size=1,  
    class_mode='binary',
    shuffle=False
)

# Load the best saved models
best_model_path_1 = 'best_model_1.keras'  
best_model_path_2 = 'best_vgg16_finetuned_model.keras'

model_1 = load_model(best_model_path_1)
model_2 = load_model(best_model_path_2)

# Evaluate the models
print("Evaluating Model 1 ")
test_loss_1, test_acc_1 = model_1.evaluate(test_generator, verbose=0)
print(f"Model 1 Test Accuracy: {test_acc_1}")

print("Evaluating Model 2 (Fine-Tuned VGG16)")
test_loss_2, test_acc_2 = model_2.evaluate(test_generator, verbose=0)
print(f"Model 2 Test Accuracy: {test_acc_2}")

# Predictions
test_steps = len(test_generator)
y_true = test_generator.classes
y_pred_1 = (model_1.predict(test_generator, steps=test_steps) > 0.5).astype("int32").flatten()
y_pred_2 = (model_2.predict(test_generator, steps=test_steps) > 0.5).astype("int32").flatten()

# Confusion Matrices
conf_matrix_1 = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred_1)
conf_matrix_2 = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred_2)
print("Confusion Matrix - Model 1:")
print(conf_matrix_1)
print("\nConfusion Matrix - Model 2:")
print(conf_matrix_2)

# Classification Reports
print("\nClassification Report - Model 1:")
print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred_1, target_names=test_generator.class_indices.keys()))

print("\nClassification Report - Model 2:")
print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred_2, target_names=test_generator.class_indices.keys()))

# Precision-Recall Curves
y_scores_1 = model_1.predict(test_generator, steps=test_steps).flatten()
y_scores_2 = model_2.predict(test_generator, steps=test_steps).flatten()
precision_1, recall_1, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_scores_1)
precision_2, recall_2, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_scores_2)

auc_1 = auc(recall_1, precision_1)
auc_2 = auc(recall_2, precision_2)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(recall_1, precision_1, label=f'Model 1 - AUC: {auc_1:.2f}')
plt.plot(recall_2, precision_2, label=f'Model 2 - AUC: {auc_2:.2f}')
plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve')
plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
plt.legend()
plt.grid()
plt.show()

# Analyze Examples of Misclassifications
misclassified_indices_1 = np.where(y_true != y_pred_1)[0]
misclassified_indices_2 = np.where(y_true != y_pred_2)[0]

print(f"Examples of Misclassifications - Model 1: {misclassified_indices_1[:5]}")
print(f"Examples of Misclassifications - Model 2: {misclassified_indices_2[:5]}")

# Visualize Misclassified Examples
def plot_misclassified_examples(generator, indices, model_name):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    for i, idx in enumerate(indices[:5]):
        img, label = generator[idx]
        plt.subplot(1, 5, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(img[0])
        plt.title(f"True: {label}, Predicted: {1-label}") 
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.suptitle(f'Misclassified Examples - {model_name}')
    plt.show()

plot_misclassified_examples(test_generator, misclassified_indices_1, "Model 1")
plot_misclassified_examples(test_generator, misclassified_indices_2, "Model 2")

CONCLUSION¶

The output provides a detailed comparison between two models for binary classification of images (cats vs. dogs):

1. Model Performance Metrics¶

  • Model 1 (Baseline VGG16 with frozen layers):

    • Test accuracy: 92.65%
    • Precision, Recall, and F1-Score are all around 0.93 for both classes (cats and dogs).
    • Confusion Matrix:
      • 925 true positives (correct predictions for one class).
      • 75 false positives (predicted as one class incorrectly).
      • 928 true negatives.
      • 72 false negatives (missed predictions for one class).
    • Observation: While Model 1 performs decently, it has relatively high false positives and false negatives, showing limitations in learning subtle differences between classes.

  • Model 2 (Fine-Tuned VGG16):

    • Test accuracy: 97.25% (substantially better than Model 1).
    • Precision, Recall, and F1-Score improved significantly, achieving 0.96 - 0.98 for both classes.
    • Confusion Matrix:
      • 981 true positives.
      • 19 false positives.
      • 964 true negatives.
      • 36 false negatives.
    • Observation: Model 2 performs significantly better due to fine-tuning, leading to reduced errors in both false positives and false negatives.

2. Why Fine-Tuning Works¶

  • Model 1:

    • Uses the pre-trained VGG16 base model with frozen layers, which retains general-purpose features learned from ImageNet.
    • Limitation: Since the base model isn't retrained, it doesn't adapt fully to task-specific features (cats vs. dogs).

  • Model 2:

    • Fine-tunes the VGG16 base by unfreezing the last few layers, allowing the model to adapt to the specific dataset.
    • This enables the model to learn task-specific features (e.g., subtle differences in texture, shape, or fur patterns), improving both precision and recall.

3. Evaluation Metrics¶

  • Accuracy: Measures the overall percentage of correct predictions. Model 2's higher accuracy (97.25%) shows its superior performance over Model 1 (92.65%).
  • Precision: Evaluates how many of the predicted positives are actually correct. Model 2 achieves better precision, meaning fewer false alarms (false positives).
  • Recall: Evaluates how many of the actual positives are correctly identified. Model 2's higher recall shows it missed fewer true cases (false negatives).
  • F1-Score: A balance between precision and recall. Model 2's F1-score reflects its ability to maintain both high precision and high recall.

4. Confusion Matrix Analysis¶

  • Model 1:
    • Higher false positives (75) and false negatives (72) indicate limited ability to differentiate between classes.
  • Model 2:
    • Drastically reduced errors with only 19 false positives and 36 false negatives, showing improved generalization.

5. Practical Implications¶

  • Precision-Recall Trade-Off:
    • Higher precision (Model 2) reduces the risk of false positives, making it more reliable in real-world scenarios.
    • Higher recall (Model 2) ensures fewer actual cases are missed, which is critical for tasks requiring high sensitivity.
  • Error Reduction:
    • Model 2's reduced misclassifications make it a better choice for applications requiring high accuracy and reliability.

6. Key Takeaways¶

  1. Fine-Tuning Matters: Adapting pre-trained models to specific tasks by fine-tuning significantly enhances their performance.
  2. Error Reduction: Fine-tuned models can reduce both false positives and false negatives, leading to better generalization.
  3. Balanced Metrics: Model 2 achieves a better balance between precision, recall, and F1-score, demonstrating its robustness.
  4. Application Insight: Model 2 is more suitable for deployment in real-world scenarios due to its higher accuracy and lower misclassification rates.
